{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Collins Street 5 pm .jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Collins St., 5 pm | artist=[[John Brack]] | year=[[1955 in art|1955]] | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=114.6 | width_metric=162.9 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Melbourne]] | museum=[[National Gallery of Victoria]] | url=http://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/col/work/3161 }} [[File:Collins St architecture.jpg|thumb|Collins Street in 2003]] '''''Collins St., 5 pm''''' is a [[1955 in art|1955]] painting by Australian artist [[John Brack]]. The painting depicts office workers walking along busy [[Collins Street, Melbourne|Collins Street]] in [[Melbourne]] after finishing work for the day{{mdash}}"Blank-faced office workers hurry by like sleep-walkers, thinking only of the pubs or their homes in the suburbs".<ref name=McDonald>{{cite web|last1=McDonald|first1=John|title=John Brack|url=http://johnmcdonald.net.au/2009/john-brack/|website=John McDonald|accessdate=21 July 2015|date=6 June 2009}}</ref> Brack conceived the work after reading [[T. S. Eliot]]'s ''[[The Waste Land]]''.<ref>Engberg, Juliana, "Collins Street, 5pm: John Brack's Enduring Cultural Icon', ''Art and Australia'', vol. 34, no. 4, 1997, pp. 513-17.</ref> It is considered a companion piece to Brack's earlier work ''[[The Bar (painting)|The Bar]]''.<ref name="abc">{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/03/19/2520543.htm|title=Gallery buys The Bar|date=19 March 2009|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=27 November 2009}}</ref>
The painting was purchased from [[Peter Bray Gallery]]<ref>"In 1953, he had his first solo exhibition at Peter Bray's Gallery in Melbourne. ''Collins Street'' was exhibited at the same gallery in March 1956 and was immediately purchased by the NGV." McKiernan, M. (2010). 'John Brack Collins Street 5 pm, 1955'. ''Occupational Medicine'', 60(2), 88-89.</ref> for the [[National Gallery of Victoria]]'s permanent Australian art collection and is exhibited in the [[Ian Potter Centre]] in [[Federation Square]] in [[Melbourne]].<ref>[http://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/col/work/3161 National Gallery of Victoria Acquisition 1956]</ref>
{{quote|Looking back on his iconic picture ... Brack found it to be “totally unsatisfactory”, because of the condescending attitude he adopted in relation to the people in the street. “I should have known,” he said, “that their lives were just as complex as mine, if not more so.”|Art critic John McDonald|<ref name=McDonald />}}
In 2011, ''Collins St., 5 pm'' was voted the most popular work in the collection of the [[National Gallery of Victoria]].<ref name="The Australian - 19Apr2011 - John Brack's Collins St, 5pm, the Most Popular Painting at NGV ">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/john-bracks-collins-st-5pm-the-most-popular-painting-at-ngv/story-fn3dxity-1226041321612|title=John Brack's Collins St, 5pm, the Most Popular Painting at NGV |last=Bennett|first=Sally|date=19 April 2011|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Limited]]|accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref>
